2012-10-01','Codeception PHP testing framework is easy to install and use. In this video I will show how to write two acceptance tests and execute them with PhpBrowser and Selenium WebDriver.','09:18',0,232,'<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/50387711?badge=0\" width=\"500\" height=\"281\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','Getting Started with Codeception','getting-started-with-codeception',0,'Vimeo','http://vimeo.com/50387711','http://b.vimeocdn.com/ts/347/175/347175847_1280.jpg','2012-11-13','pub'),(80,2,'2012-06-05','Annotations are more than phpdoc comments, they\'re a fully-featured way of including additional information alongside your code.  We might have rejected an RFC to add support into the PHP core, but the community has embraced this tool anyway!  This session shows you who is doing what with annotations, and will give you some ideas on how to use the existing tools in your own projects to keep life simple. Developers, architects and anyone responsible for the technical direction of an application should attend this session.','47:15',0,59,'<iframe width=\"450\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/1RkAyDT4_Mo\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>','<iframe src=\"http://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/embed_code/13206296\" width=\"400\" height=\"356\" frameborder=\"0\" marginwidth=\"0\" marginheight=\"0\" scrolling=\"no\" style=\"border:1px solid #CCC;border-width:1px 1px 0;margin-bottom:5px\" allowfullscreen webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen> </iframe>',NULL,'en','Annotating with Annotations','annotating-with-annotations',0,'Forum Paris 2012','http://afup.org/pages/forumphp2012/','http://img.youtube.com/vi/1RkAyDT4_Mo/default.jpg','2012-11-17','pub'),(81,2,'2012-06-05','cette conférence a pour but de montrer comment PHP fonctionne de l\'intérieur, pour mieux l\'appréhender et le maîtriser de l\'extérieur.\r\nL\'axe de reflexion sera la performance du langage, et nous allons concrètement analyser certaines parties pour expliquer certains faits : les quotes, les tableaux, les objets et les fonctions, le masquage d\'erreurs, la sérialisation et encore bien d\'autres choses. A bas les mythes et trolls ridicules que nous connaissons au sujet de notre langage fétiche !','47:27',0,56,'<iframe width=\"475\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/NSUaOMFNq18\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'fr','Anatomie, fonctionnement et performances de PHP','anatomie-fonctionnement-et-performances-de-php',0,'Forum Paris 2012','http://afup.org/pages/forumphp2012','http://img.youtube.com/vi/NSUaOMFNq18/default.jpg','2012-11-17','pub'),(82,2,NULL,'MySQL dispose maintenant d\'un driver PHP natif sous licence PHP. Ce nouveau driver sera le driver par défaut à partir de PHP 5.4','45:26',0,40,'<iframe width=\"475\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/Uhen83wX1PM\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'fr','fonctions avancés du driver MySQL natif pour PHP','fonctions-avancs-du-driver-mysql-natif-pour-php',0,'Forum Paris 2012','http://afup.org/pages/forumphp2012','http://img.youtube.com/vi/Uhen83wX1PM/default.jpg','2012-11-17','pub'),(83,2,'2012-06-06','At Etsy, we continuously deploy code. New features and bug fixes can go from development to production in 20 minutes. We have maintained this low barrier to deployment over the past year despite nearly doubling the number of people that can deploy. Communication has a huge impact on the velocity of development and moving forward.','45:46',0,58,'<iframe width=\"475\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/kHQdFZ0abR8\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','Scaling Communication through Continuous Integration','scaling-communication-through-continuous-integration',0,'Forum Paris 2012','http://afup.org/pages/forumphp2012','http://img.youtube.com/vi/kHQdFZ0abR8/default.jpg','2012-11-17','pub'),(84,2,'2012-06-05','We use static code analysis tools more often these days that create great reports and funky graphs. But do we understand what it all means? Software metrics tends to be magic numbers for a lot of people, but they don’t really have to be. I will introduce you to a few basic, the most popular software metrics and tools. I will explain to you what they mean and how you can use them to produce better software.','47:18',0,46,'<iframe width=\"475\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/fxAb6__wRqg\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>','<iframe src=\"http://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/embed_code/13207973\" width=\"375\" height=\"320\" frameborder=\"0\" marginwidth=\"0\" marginheight=\"0\" scrolling=\"no\" style=\"border:1px solid #CCC;border-width:1px 1px 0;margin-bottom:5px\" allowfullscreen webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen> </iframe>',NULL,'en','Behind The Magic Numbers, Software Metrics In Practice','behind-the-magic-numbers-software-metrics-in-practice',0,'Forum Paris 2012','http://afup.org/pages/forumphp2012/','http://img.youtube.com/vi/fxAb6__wRqg/default.jpg','2012-11-17','pub'),(85,2,'2012-06-05','A look at the state of PHP in 2012. Where are we, how did we get here and how does PHP fit into the current infrastructure ecosystem of the Web? Plus, a quick tour of what is new and cool in PHP 5.4.','01:04:06',0,51,'<iframe width=\"475\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/9vk18tKoIbE\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','PHP in 2012','php-in-2012',0,'Forum PHP Paris 2012','http://afup.org/pages/forumphp2012/','http://img.youtube.com/vi/9vk18tKoIbE/default.jpg','2012-11-17','pub'),(86,2,'2012-06-05','En partant d’un environnement LAMP classique, nous vous montrerons comment remplacer ou simplement configurer les différentes composantes d’une architecture web afin d’améliorer les performances de votre application sans même toucher au code source. Mots clés : Apache, Nginx, mariaDB, performance, serveur, poney :)','48:10',0,58,'<iframe width=\"475\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/R0Gbh5C-lCw\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'fr','Coup de pied dans la LAMP','coup-de-pied-dans-la-lamp',0,'Forum PHP Paris 2012','http://afup.org/pages/forumphp2012','http://img.youtube.com/vi/R0Gbh5C-lCw/default.jpg','2012-11-17','pub'),(87,2,'2012-06-05','Quand on partage la passion de PHP, le fossé culturel et la barrière de 3 langues ne font peur à personne !','47:18',0,39,'<iframe width=\"475\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/tiOEW67I-Mg\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'fr','Au secours mes développeurs parlent Chinois!','au-secours-mes-dveloppeurs-parlent-chinois',0,'Forum PHP Paris 2012','http://afup.org/pages/forumphp2012','http://img.youtube.com/vi/tiOEW67I-Mg/default.jpg','2012-11-17','pub'),(88,2,'2012-06-06','Les cycles de développement des applications raccourcissent de plus en plus. La pression se fait plus forte sur les équipes de développement qui sont poussées à développer en mode mercenaire, où seul le résultat immédiat compte. Cette vision est généralement contre-productive sur le long-terme car on passe beaucoup plus de temps à maintenir une application qu\'à la développer. Il est donc primordial de s\'assurer de sa qualité au delà de l\'adéquation avec le besoin fonctionnel. Cela passe par de nombreux éléments dont bien entendu la qualité du code source mais pas seulement. La présence de documentations pertinentes et à jour, les types et l\'étendue des tests mis en place, l\'architecture de l\'application ou encore sa portabilité sont autant de facteurs clés du succès d\'un projet.','49:45',0,46,'<iframe width=\"475\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/w-PFFXOXqls\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>','<iframe src=\"http://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/embed_code/13221903\" width=\"400\" height=\"356\" frameborder=\"0\" marginwidth=\"0\" marginheight=\"0\" scrolling=\"no\" style=\"border:1px solid #CCC;border-width:1px 1px 0;margin-bottom:5px\" allowfullscreen webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen> </iframe>',NULL,'fr','La qualité au-delà du code','la-qualit-au-del-du-code',0,'Forum PHP Paris 2012','http://afup.org/pages/forumphp2012','http://img.youtube.com/vi/w-PFFXOXqls/default.jpg','2012-11-17','pub'),(89,2,'2012-06-06','Le forum PHP 2012 s\'est clôturé par une table ronde pendant laquelle des décideurs importants ont évoqués le langage PHP et son écosystème.','01:15:06',0,87,'<iframe width=\"475\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/4ex9UIfQ2Aw\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'fr','retrouvez la table ronde du forum PHP','retrouvez-la-table-ronde-du-forum-php',0,'Forum PHP Paris 2012','http://afup.org/pages/forumphp2012','http://img.youtube.com/vi/4ex9UIfQ2Aw/default.jpg','2012-11-17','pub'),(90,2,'2012-06-06','this talk we will present a simple web application built with Zend Framework 2. We will show the new features of the framework, such as the new MVC layer, the Event Manager, the Dependency Injection and much more. The aim of this talk is how to start programming with the new architecture of ZF2. Moreover, we will show the differences with the version 1 of the framework and how to migrate applications from ZF1 to ZF2.','48:56',0,69,'<iframe width=\"475\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/GSSMbshwDnA\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','A quick start on Zend Framework 2','a-quick-start-on-zend-framework-2',0,'Forum PHP Paris 2012','http://afup.org/pages/forumphp2012','http://img.youtube.com/vi/GSSMbshwDnA/default.jpg','2012-11-17','pub'),(91,2,'2012-06-06','Après de nombreuses collaborations réussies avec Zend, NBS System a mis en place une offre d’hébergement spécifique qui tire parti de l’infrastructure de Cloud privé de NBS System & des outils Zend et qui permet d’obtenir un très haut niveau de service pour les applications PHP, en particulier dans le domaine du e-commerce (Magento, Prestashop, etc.).\r\n\r\nLors de cette session, Emile Heitor, CTO de NBS System, vous présentera l’architecture technique mise en place et les avantages que cette plateforme apporte pour gérer les applications, que ce soit du point de vue de l’hébergeur, d’un intégrateur web ou du client final. Les composants suivants du Zend Cloud seront ainsi abordés :\r\n- Zend Server (et code Tracer) qui permet d’obtenir les indications sur la qualité du code, les bugs applicatifs, ainsi qu’une analyse fine du comportement du site\r\n- MySQL Enterprise, afin de pouvoir contrôler les ressources allouées à la base de données, sa santé, sa performance et son état en terme de sécurité\r\n- Munin, qui permet de connaître tous les paramètres vitaux d’un OS Linux\r\n- Xen pour reconfigurer à la volée les serveurs et en étendre la puissance','38:39',0,47,'<iframe width=\"475\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/X6LKX4SqTSo\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'fr','Scalabilité sans limite grâce au Zend Cloud','scalabilit-sans-limite-grce-au-zend-cloud',0,'Forum PHP Paris 2012','http://afup.org/pages/forumphp2012','http://img.youtube.com/vi/X6LKX4SqTSo/default.jpg','2012-11-17','pub'),(92,1,'2012-11-21','Programming paradigms are fun to debate and talk about. In this short video, we\'ll talk about the differences between Procedural, Object Oriented and Functional programming. We\'ll also explore what happens when these paradigms cross over each other.','4:25',0,183,'<iframe width=\"500\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/CV4vPsEizJM\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','Programming With Anthony - Paradigm Soup','programming-with-anthony-paradigm-soup',0,'ircmaxwell\'s blog','http://blog.ircmaxell.com/2012/11/programming-with-anthony-paradigm-soup.html','http://img.youtube.com/vi/CV4vPsEizJM/default.jpg','2012-11-25','pub'),(93,1,'2012-03-07','The screencast series is based on the blog posts by the creator of Symfony2 Fabien Potencier: http://fabien.potencier.org/article/50/create-your-own-framework-on-top-of-the-symfony2-components-part-1','12:40',0,394,'<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/38063067?badge=0\" width=\"475\" height=\"281\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','Episode 1 - Creating Own PHP Framework Using Symfony2 Components','episode-1-creating-own-php-framework-using-symfony2-components',0,'Object Oriented PHP','http://object-oriented-php.com/','http://b.vimeocdn.com/ts/261/700/261700247_960.jpg','2012-11-26','pub'),(94,1,'2012-03-08','In the second episode of the series we’ll look at the most fundamental component in the Symfony2 Components suite – HTTPFoundation Component.\r\nSymfony2 had taken a step back from the ugly global variables and based its architecture on the most basic principles: Requests and Responses.\r\nUsing these makes building your PHP applications fun again!','20:59',0,181,'<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/38133505\" width=\"475\" height=\"300\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','Episode 2 - Creating Own PHP Framework Using Symfony2 Components','episode-2-creating-own-php-framework-using-symfony2-components',0,'Object Oriented PHP','http://object-oriented-php.com/2012/03/screencast-series-creating-own-php-framework-using-symfony2-components-episode-2/','http://b.vimeocdn.com/ts/262/250/262250267_960.jpg','2012-11-28','pub'),(95,1,'2012-03-10','In this episode we’ll create the heart of our framework – the front controller. It’s primary role in our framework will be dispatching HTTP responses based on the HTTP requests (URL the client has called). In order to do that we’ll be reordering the files into the logical directory structure and writing some amazing code. Enjoy!','29:23',0,183,'<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/38198191?badge=0\" width=\"475\" height=\"281\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','Episode 3 - Creating Own PHP Framework Using Symfony2 Components','episode-3-creating-own-php-framework-using-symfony2-components',0,'Object Oriented PHP','http://object-oriented-php.com/2012/03/screencast-series-creating-own-php-framework-using-symfony2-components-episode-3/','http://b.vimeocdn.com/ts/262/750/262750365_960.jpg','2012-11-29','pub'),(96,1,'2012-03-12','In this episode we’ll use the Symfony2 Component Routing, which will take care of mapping the URLs to the file paths. One of the advantages of the Routing component is the ability to create dynamical paths. To convert something like /hello?name=Andrey into /name/Andrey we’ll take advantage of RouteCollection, URLMatcher and RequestConext – the classes bundled with the Routing component.','23:14',0,177,'<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/38335943?badge=0\" width=\"500\" height=\"281\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','Episode 4 - Creating Own PHP Framework Using Symfony2 Components','episode-4-creating-own-php-framework-using-symfony2-components',0,'Object Oriented PHP','http://object-oriented-php.com/2012/03/screencast-series-creating-own-php-framework-using-symfony2-components-episode-4/','http://b.vimeocdn.com/ts/263/783/263783184_960.jpg','2012-11-29','pub'),(97,1,'2012-03-14','Today we’ll cover one of the corner stones of modern application architecture – the controller. Its mission is to generate a Response based on the information provided by the client Request. Put in simplest terms: the controller contains the business logic of your application. Say, a client requests an URL example.com/is_leap_year/2012. Instead of writing everything inside of the file leap_year.php where the presentational markup and programming logic get mixed, we’ll move the leap year calculations into a very digestible container – the controller.','16:14',0,288,'<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/38468735\" width=\"475\" height=\"300\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','Episode 5 - Creating Own PHP Framework Using Symfony2 Components','episode-5-creating-own-php-framework-using-symfony2-components',0,'Object Oriented PHP','http://object-oriented-php.com/2012/03/screencast-series-creating-own-php-framework-using-symfony2-components-episode-5/','http://b.vimeocdn.com/ts/264/794/264794148_960.jpg','2012-11-29','pub'),(98,1,'2012-03-19','We’ve been stuck with procedural code in our framework for the educational purposes. It is time to grow up and use object oriented style. In this episode we’ll convert our controller to the class. Then we’ll optimize the object instantiation by using another handy Symfony2 Component – HTTPKernel.','13:47',0,185,'<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/38746606\" width=\"475\" height=\"300\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','Episode 6 - Creating Own PHP Framework Using Symfony2 Components','episode-6-creating-own-php-framework-using-symfony2-components',0,'Object Oriented PHP','http://object-oriented-php.com/2012/03/screencast-series-creating-own-php-framework-using-symfony2-components-episode-6/','http://b.vimeocdn.com/ts/266/855/266855830_960.jpg','2012-11-29','pub'),(99,1,'2012-03-21','We’ve been working on our framework for quite some time now. We’ve been adding some important features by enabling new Symfony2 Components. But with the time our code base grew and now if you take a look our “framework” code it’s a mess. It’s time to do some serious refactoring. And from now on the framework we’re building will have a name – Simplex!\r\nIn this episode we’re going to do the following:\r\n- the front controller (/web/front.php) will be the boiler-plate to initialize the framework and the application\r\n- the framework itself (/src/Simplex) will abstract the handling of incoming Requests into class that could be reused when creating other web sites and applications\r\n- the application (/src/Calendar) will handle the business logic – in our case will calculate the leap year and do other interesting stuff with time continuum\r\n- the configuration (/src/app.php) will take care of routing and customization of the framework','15:46',0,198,'<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/38777562\" width=\"475\" height=\"300\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','Episode 7 - Creating Own PHP Framework Using Symfony2 Components','episode-7-creating-own-php-framework-using-symfony2-components',0,'Object Oriented PHP','http://object-oriented-php.com/2012/03/screencast-series-creating-own-php-framework-using-symfony2-components-episode-7/','http://b.vimeocdn.com/ts/267/091/267091979_960.jpg','2012-11-29','pub'),(100,1,'2012-04-08','In this episode of the series we are going to ensure the durability of our code by including one of the most important components of the modern application design – Unit Testing.','26:51',0,200,'<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/39978446\" width=\"475\" height=\"300\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','Episode 8 - Creating Own PHP Framework Using Symfony2 Components','episode-8-creating-own-php-framework-using-symfony2-components',0,'Object Oriented PHP','http://object-oriented-php.com/2012/04/screencast-series-creating-own-php-framework-using-symfony2-components-episode-8/','http://b.vimeocdn.com/ts/276/048/276048461_1280.jpg','2012-11-29','pub'),(101,1,'2012-04-11','We’ve gone a long way to build a nicely decoupled and object-oriented Framework. One thing is missing though – to add the possibility to extend our Framework with the arbitrary code modules.\r\nIn this episode we are going to build a “module” that will hook into the live cycle of the Framework – just like Drupal modules do!','18:09',0,185,'<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/40121621\" width=\"475\" height=\"300\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','Episode 9 - Creating Own PHP Framework Using Symfony2 Components','episode-9-creating-own-php-framework-using-symfony2-components',0,'Object Oriented PHP','http://object-oriented-php.com/2012/04/screencast-series-creating-own-php-framework-using-symfony2-components-episode-9/','http://b.vimeocdn.com/ts/277/081/277081963_960.jpg','2012-11-29','pub'),(102,1,'2012-04-19','It is time to take a look at the “most important piece of code in the HttpKernel component”, as Fabien Potencier himself puts it – HttpKernelInterface. Among other things this interface supports native HTTP-Caching, the feature we’ll be exporing in this episode.','06:38',0,170,'<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/40619884\" width=\"475\" height=\"300\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','Episode 10 - Creating Own PHP Framework Using Symfony2 Components','episode-10-creating-own-php-framework-using-symfony2-components',0,'Object Oriented PHP','http://object-oriented-php.com/2012/04/screencast-series-creating-own-php-framework-using-symfony2-components-episode-10/','http://b.vimeocdn.com/ts/280/781/280781257_960.jpg','2012-11-29','pub'),(103,1,'2012-11-29','In this part we’ll be exploring the powers of wonderfull HttpKernelInterface even further by adding even more listeners to the request. This is generally a very good way to add a new functionality, because it lets you to concentrate on the single feature, test this feature, and then integrate in the flow of the request – wherever it fits.','26:36',0,910,'<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/54500464?color=9ac5d6\" width=\"475\" height=\"300\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','Episode 11 - Creating Own PHP Framework Using Symfony2 Components','episode-11-creating-own-php-framework-using-symfony2-components',0,'Object Oriented PHP','http://object-oriented-php.com/2012/11/sreencast-series-creating-own-php-freamework-using-symfony2-components-episode-11/','http://b.vimeocdn.com/ts/376/858/376858578_1280.jpg','2012-11-29','pub'),(104,1,'2012-11-17','Programming is a very involved career path, with many ongoing requirements to stay up on. Here we talk about those requirements and how to equip yourself with the tools to succeed.','36:39',0,86,'<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/54379268?badge=0\" width=\"475\" height=\"375\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','How to act like you (maybe actually) care about your work','how-to-act-like-you-maybe-actually-care-about-your-work',0,'Vimeo','http://vimeo.com/54379268','http://b.vimeocdn.com/ts/375/968/375968035_640.jpg','2012-11-29','pub'),(105,1,'2012-12-01','This talk gives a basic overview of the different types of tests and tools out there, and then goes into specific detail of writing your first Selenium test in PHPUnit.','09:27',0,365,'<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/54691719?badge=0\" width=\"475\" height=\"375\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','Introduction to PHP Integration Testing','introduction-to-php-integration-testing',0,'Vimeo','http://vimeo.com/54691719','http://b.vimeocdn.com/ts/378/262/378262535_640.jpg','2012-12-03','pub'),(106,1,'2012-11-01','Atlanta PHP User Group presentation','53:49',0,136,'<iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/53746372?badge=0\" width=\"475\" height=\"375\" frameborder=\"0\" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','The Magical World of Gearman','the-magical-world-of-gearman',0,'Altanta PHP User Group','http://atlantaphp.org/video','http://b.vimeocdn.com/ts/371/385/371385882_1280.jpg','2012-12-03','pub'),(107,2,'2012-10-23','Routing is an integral part of the Zend Framework 2 MVC system. It takes your request and extracts parameters out of it for further processing. This talk will introduce you to the powerful feature of the new routing process and will enable you to use the router to its full extent. This includes utilizing B-tree routing for better performance, having localized routes and much more.','56:12',0,44,'<iframe width=\"475\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/PsgXWigf5dw\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','Introducing the New Zend Framework 2 Router','introducing-the-new-zend-framework-2-router',0,'ZendTechnologies YouTube Channel','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PsgXWigf5dw&feature=plcp','http://img.youtube.com/vi/PsgXWigf5dw/default.jpg','2012-12-04','pub'),(108,2,'2012-10-24','Domain-driven design is a collaborative process involving both domain experts and software practitioners that attempts to address issues of complexity in software. This process is described in the book Domain-Driven Design (Addison-Wesley 2004) written by Eric Evans. Domain-driven design starts with the assertion that (for almost all software) complexity is in the domain, not in the technology. Accordingly, we must let technology play a supporting role. Domain-driven design attempts to focus on and distill the core domain for a given project. Philosopher and scientist Alfred Korzybski said, \"The map is not the territory.\" As such, a person practicing domain-driven design does not attempt to model reality. Instead, domain experts and software practitioners use a mental model as a tool for solving problems within a given domain. The domain experts and software practitioners collaborate to explore and develop this model. No software of any reasonable scope has just one model. We will look at the concept of a bounded context within which each model can be isolated and explored. Within a bounded context, collaborators must speak a ubiquitous language in order to reason about and discuss the model. We will also talk about domain-driven design\'s building block patterns including entities, value objects, aggregates, repositories, services, and domain events. We will look at domain-driven design practices including supple design, strategic design, and distillation of the core. We will see how test-driven development can be used as a means of exploring the model. Examples in PHP will be provided of the building block patterns as well as other techniques including closure of operations, intention revealing interfaces, side-effect free functions, and assertions.','1:05:37',0,78,'<iframe width=\"475\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/RNUn2R7TptM\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>','<script async class=\"speakerdeck-embed\" data-id=\"508850b1db554a000206fc69\" data-ratio=\"1.33333333333333\" src=\"//speakerdeck.com/assets/embed.js\"></script>',NULL,'en','Domain-Driven Design','domain-driven-design',0,'ZendTechnologies YouTube Channel','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RNUn2R7TptM&feature=plcp','http://img.youtube.com/vi/RNUn2R7TptM/default.jpg','2012-12-04','pub'),(109,2,'2012-10-23','MySQL users commonly ask: Here\'s my table, what indexes do I need? Why aren\'t my indexes helping me? Don\'t indexes cause overhead? This talk gives you some practical answers, with a step by step method for finding the queries you need to optimize, and choosing the best indexes for them.','1:01:37',0,58,'<iframe width=\"475\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/ELR7-RdU9XU\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>','<iframe src=\"http://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/embed_code/14886467\" width=\"400\" height=\"356\" frameborder=\"0\" marginwidth=\"0\" marginheight=\"0\" scrolling=\"no\" style=\"border:1px solid #CCC;border-width:1px 1px 0;margin-bottom:5px\" allowfullscreen webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen> </iframe>',NULL,'en','How to Design Indexes, Really','how-to-design-indexes-really',0,'ZendTechnologies YouTube Channel','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ELR7-RdU9XU&feature=plcp','http://img.youtube.com/vi/ELR7-RdU9XU/default.jpg','2012-12-04','pub'),(110,2,'2012-10-23','This panel of Shawn Stratton, Evan Coury, Mike Willbanks and Matthew O\'Phinney will present information about three applications built using Zend Framework 2 during it\'s early development and how their feedback help influence and shape the direction of the development. Come see how these early adopters feel about the final ZF2, using open source early and how this active participation helps shape ZF2.','1:03:17',0,51,'<iframe width=\"475\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/MAQvj_YeN5U\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','Zend Framework 2 - Practical Experience From the Trenches','zend-framework-2-practical-experience-from-the-trenches',0,'ZendTechnologies YouTube Channel','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MAQvj_YeN5U&feature=plcp','http://img.youtube.com/vi/MAQvj_YeN5U/default.jpg','2012-12-04','pub'),(111,2,'2012-10-25','Unlike relational databases, document databases like CouchDB and MongoDB do not directly support entity relationships. This talk will explore patterns of modeling one-to-many and many-to-many entity relationships in a document database. These patterns include using an embedded JSON array, relating documents using identifiers, using a list of keys, and using relationship documents. This talk will explore how these entity relationship patterns equate to how entities are joined in a relational database. We\'ll take a look at the relevant differences between document databases and relational databases. For example, document databases do not have tables, each document can have its own schema, there is no built-in concept of relationships between documents, views/indexes are queried directly instead of being used to optimize more generalized queries, a column within a result set can contain a mix of logical data types, and there is typically no support for transactions across document boundaries.','40:34',0,66,'<iframe width=\"475\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/lQLTiX93PL8\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>','<script async class=\"speakerdeck-embed\" data-id=\"5089650d36136c00020063eb\" data-ratio=\"1.33333333333333\" src=\"//speakerdeck.com/assets/embed.js\"></script>',NULL,'en','Entity Relationships in a Document Database','entity-relationships-in-a-document-database',0,'ZendTechnologies YouTube Channel','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lQLTiX93PL8&feature=plcp','http://img.youtube.com/vi/lQLTiX93PL8/default.jpg','2012-12-04','pub'),(112,2,'2012-10-24','HTML5 is the future of web development - but the main focus of the upcoming standard is on JavaScript APIs, not on HTML5 markup. Come to this session to learn about the JavaScript APIs HTML5 has to offer, see many live code demos showcasing features and failures, and listen to war stories from real-world projects. Not everything in HTML5 will appeal to every project, but there are many hightlights, and also some lowlights.','58:42',0,63,'<iframe width=\"475\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/lc1rdth6O8c\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','HTML5 APIs','html5-apis',0,'ZendTechnologies YouTube Channel','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lc1rdth6O8c&feature=plcp','http://img.youtube.com/vi/lc1rdth6O8c/default.jpg','2012-12-04','pub'),(113,2,'2012-10-24','Zend Server is best known for its robust monitoring toolset. But what good is a monitoring toolset if you don\'t have the tools to fix the issues that come up? In this session we will go over how you can discover where performance issues are occuring in your application and how you can implement fixes using various performance features in our flagship product.','52:03',0,54,'<iframe width=\"475\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/RMwoamgMKfE\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','Using Zend Server Performance Tools','using-zend-server-performance-tools',0,'ZendTechnologies YouTube Channel','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RMwoamgMKfE&feature=plcp','http://img.youtube.com/vi/RMwoamgMKfE/default.jpg','2012-12-04','pub'),(114,2,'2012-10-25','Software is a craft. Like any craft, the software we build can be either quickly created to solve an immediate problem, or well crafted for longevity. Typically in software, we look at how extensible and maintainable a system may be in order to judge its quality. In this session, we\'ll take a practical example, and develop it from a quick one-liner into a re-usable component. Along the way, we\'ll discuss the choices we make as developers, and how they affect both how we develop and the results we produce -- choices ranging from testing to considering scalability, to re-use with alternate configuration. The goal is to inspire developers to craft beautiful software.','49:48',0,137,'<iframe width=\"475\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/mQsQ6QZ4dGg\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','Designing Beautiful Software','designing-beautiful-software',0,'ZendTechnologies YouTube Channel','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mQsQ6QZ4dGg&feature=plcp','http://img.youtube.com/vi/mQsQ6QZ4dGg/default.jpg','2012-12-04','pub'),(115,2,'2012-10-23','In this keynote session, Andi Gutmans will explore the latest innovations around cloud and mobile development, along with highlighting some of the newest innovations unveiled in Zend Framework 2.','1:18:24',0,38,'<iframe width=\"475\" height=\"315\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/xvyiNb1G3dI\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>',NULL,NULL,'en','ZendCon 2012 Opening Keynote','zendcon-2012-opening-keynote',0,'ZendTechnologies YouTube Channel','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xvyiNb1G3dI&feature=plcp',